To make sure that our customers aren't fat-fingering their email address, we should be checking their domain so that things like `.con` don't get saved. There is already checking in-place to make sure that the form of the email address is correct. The next step is to check the domain to make sure that an email server is actually setup for it (this is called an MX DNS record).

Here is the code for a frontend API that will check for MX records:

```
import type { NextApiRequest, NextApiResponse } from 'next';
import dns from 'dns/promises';
import NextCors from 'nextjs-cors';

import { RE_REDBALLOON_SUBDOMAINS } from 'src/data/constants';

export default async function handler(req: NextApiRequest, res: NextApiResponse) {
  await NextCors(req, res, {
    // the methods this API supports
    methods: ['POST'],
    // enable CORS for sub-domains of redballoon.work
    origin: RE_REDBALLOON_SUBDOMAINS,
  });
  // We don't want to allow people to use us for the DNS equivalent of DDoS.
  // Requiring POST enables CSRF checking in the middleware.
  if (req.method !== 'POST') {
    res.status(400).send('Endpoint does not exist!');
    return;
  }
  const { domain } = req.body;

  try {
    await dns.resolveMx(domain as string);
    res.json({ domain_found: true });
  } catch (err) {
    res.json({ domain_found: false });
  }
}
```

